Date:10/7/2008 6:49:49 PM
From:Tapcon

On a market timing note, does anyone put much weight in the VIX being as high
as it is now? I think the only time it was higher was during the '87 crash.

Well, the VIX sure would seem like a contributing indicator that, even if we
are NOT in the latter innings of this ballgame, we could reasonably expect some
sort of rally very soon.

I'm looking too at the average peak-to-trough decline in recession-induced bear
markets for the last 50 years and it shows the average decline of nine such
bear markets was about 27%. As of today, the S&P is down 37% from its high. See
the chart in the following article.

http://www.hussman.net/rsi/recessionbears.htm
Note the article was written in Sept, 2007.

Looking at the range, rather than just the average decline, however, it's not
exactly a tight statistical distribution! In the 2000 recession-induced bear
market, the decline was close to 50%. The global financial system crisis would
suggest this is not your average bear market. Having said that, I have to think
that the upside/downside risk is improving daily. There is an enormous amount
of fear out there.
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:10/7/2008 8:01:01 PM
From:anializer
Keep in mind that the average loss for all bear market declines of the past 80
years has been 30%, but the average loss for those bear markets lasting a year
or more has been -42%. And that's an average. From peak to today the Dow
decline is about average for bears lasting a year or more. My tendency is to
dispel the idea that the magnitude of this one can be predicted based on past
bear markets as we are in a new frontier. But its certainly worse than average.
%EOM----------------------

